<TEXT>
temple universitys striking professors 
rejected a second contract offer sunday night as the threat of 
canceling hundreds of classes for the entire semester loomed 
common pleas judge samuel lehrer planned to reopen a hearing 
monday into the universitys request that he force the professors 
back to work 
the proposal which union members said offered little new was 
rejected by a vote of 372 to 62 
if pickets are still marching tuesday 40 percent or 1900 of 
temples 4700 classes will be canceled for lack of a professor 
university officials say there is no alternative because there 
wont be enough days to make up lost class time before the spring 
semester starts 
patricia bradley a journalism professor said 445 union members 
and 107 nonduespaying members attended sunday nights meeting 
only duespaying members were allowed to vote she said the union 
leadership recommended rejection of the offer 
the proposal offered 5 percent salary increases over four years 
instead of previous two and threeyear offers and retained a 
request that the professors contribute 260 a year toward health 
insurance costs 
they think well just get tired and give up bradley said 
its a unionbusting strike i think thats generally 
accepted 
temples chief negotiator bob harrington said he was very 
disappointed by the vote he said the union broke agreements that 
the entire bargaining unit would vote on the proposal not just 
duespaying members and that the union leadership would not 
recommend how to vote 
the strike began sept 4 when the teachers rejected 5 percent 
increases over the next two years the teachers whose salary 
averages about 45500 want 7 percent pay increases and do not 
want to pay more for health care 
temple an independent university that receives substantial 
state support went to court after the first rejection seeking a 
court order to force teachers be ordered to return to class 
the number of faculty members on strike is unclear university 
officials and the temple association of university professionals 
which represents 1100 faculty members refuse to offer any 
estimates 
judge lehrer held two days of hearings and got both sides to 
agree to the vote on the new offer both sides would return to 
court monday if the offer was rejected he said 
meanwhile some of the schools 30000 students have blocked 
city streets daily and stood outside a courtroom chanting their 
protest of anything less than a fully operational university some 
were arrested for invading liacouras office 
time has already run out for some students missing one or more 
classes they need for a degree 
the whole thing stinks said james cunningham 20 a 
sophomore in radio television and film who was one of more than 
100 students who have withdrawn from school the deadline for 
withdrawal from school with a full refund is oct 8 
some 23000 students are missing at least one class in the fall 
semester and 6000 have had no classes at all because of the 
walkout 
they are yanking the carpet from under my feet said doug 
miller 27 a senior architecture student if classes dont resume 
he will not be taking enough credits to be classified as a 
fulltime studnet and could lose at least part of his financial 
aid 
temple lawyer john langel said that if the offer is rejected 
all classes that arent meeting by tuesday will be canceled 
this is not going to be an educational institution said 
striking history professor michael harris its going to be a 
phony basically this institution is folding 
</TEXT>
