<TEXT>
elections for the nations 435 house seats are 
likely to yield only slight shifts in power but analysts caution 
that this years voting could be among the most volatile and 
unpredictable in years 
novembers balloting will follow one of the strangest 18 
months in recent political history analyst charles cook says of 
a period that has seen upheavals in eastern europe the persian 
gulf domestic issues and the american economy 
few are willing to bet on where it all will lead but most 
analysts and operatives are guessing that democrats will pad their 
258to176 majority by less than 10 seats 
in normal times that would be a facesaving outcome for 
republicans as the party in control of the white house the gop 
historically could expect to lose 15 or more house seats in an 
offyear election 
several factors would seem to favor the gop this time around 
president bush enjoys nearrecord popularity ratings his standing 
increased by his handling of the middle east crisis and polls show 
a general public disgust with congress which is controlled by the 
democrats 
but on the other side of the ledger the economy among the 
most powerful determinants of political fortune is headed 
downward and republicans are being forced to defend more socalled 
open seats where there is no incumbent seeking reelection 
because 11 otherwise safe gop house members are running for the 
senate or state offices 
the effect of the volatility has been to put most races into 
slow motion congress which had planned to adjourn by oct 5 so 
members could go home and campaign now is unlikely to get out of 
washington until oct 20 or so 
issues that have taken on local importance from abortion to 
taxes and the savings and loan crisis have had to compete for air 
time and headlines with developments in iraq and kuwait political 
experts say the effect will be to compress the intense part of the 
election season into the final two weeks 
for one in five house districts that will make no difference 
seventysix incumbent lawmakers 42 democrats and 34 republicans 
will coast to reelection without major party opposition 
and as has become common in house contests few of their 
colleagues have much to worry about political analysts single out 
fewer than two dozen races where the incumbent is endangered 
topping that list are reps frank annunzio dill charles 
pashayan rcalif and denny smith rore all of whom are linked 
to the 500 billion scandal over the failure of the savings and 
loan industry 
a handful of others are in trouble because of political or 
ethical problems 
rep arlan stangeland rminn got in hot water for charging 
taxpayers for hundreds of longdistance calls to a female former 
employee of a lobbying firm 
it was revealed that rep roy dyson dmd who accepts large 
contributions from the defense industry in his capacity as an armed 
services committee member claimed conscientious objector status 
during the vietnam war 
rep stan parris rva said during a debate with his 
democratic opponent that he opposes affirmative action because it 
is worse to discriminate against majorities than against racial 
minorities 
and always vulnerable are freshmen many of whom won narrowly in 
1988 and have yet to establish themselves firmly in their new 
seats ben jones dga george sangmeister dill bill 
sarpalius dtexas greg laughlin dtexas peter hoagland dneb 
jolene unsoeld dwash craig james rfla ron machtley rri 
and peter smith rvt 
most of the action and the attention of democratic and 
republican party operatives focuses on the 2 open seats where 
there is no incumbent eleven are seats previously held by 
democrats and 18 were formerly gop seats 
one hotspot is maines first district where democrat joseph 
brennan is running to get back his old job as governor fighting 
for brennans house seat are democratic state sen tom andrews and 
republican david emery who is making a comeback bid 
also tough for democrats to defend is the cincinnati district of 
thomas luken who is retiring lukens son mayor charles luken is 
vying against ken blackwell a former cincinnati mayor and official 
of the department of housing and urban development blackwell is 
the gops best hope of electing a black republican to a house seat 
in five decades 
a slugfest has developed in the texas where democratic rep 
marvin leath is retiring state sen chet edwards a democrat is 
running to replace him against republican hugh shine a state house 
member shine has been attacking edwards for appearing at a 
fundraiser for a gay and lesbian group in houston last year 
democrats see their best hopes at picking open seats in 
arkansas where democratturnedrepublican tommy robinson left his 
seat to run for governor and in rhode island hawaii iowa and 
idaho where republican house members are running for senate seats 
</TEXT>
