<TEXT>
the burst of repression expected to 
follow this summers election victory by islamic fundamentalists 
hasnt materialized 
take the case of tipasa this mediterranean resort welcomes tens 
of thousands of european and algerian tourists a year to pristine 
beaches and extensive roman ruins 
not long after the 15000 residents elected a council dominated 
by the islamic salvation front fis posters went up announcing a 
ban against shorts 
the news quickly reaching europe was portrayed as evidence the 
fundamentalists knew no limits in imposing strict morality how 
could shorts be banned in a beach town 
the impression of firebreathing fundamentalists imposing a 
draconian crackdown killed the season 
june and july were just dead there were almost no 
europeans ahmed mansour remarked on the empty terrace of his 
restaurant 
but town administrator mohammed essamelli says the reality of 
the ban was more complicated 
first this laws been here since 1965 said essamelli 
all the new council did was say they intended to enforce it 
second the law does not affect tipasas beaches where men and 
women in western swimwear outnumber those in long robes 20 to one 
it covers only the town center and was modeled on similar rules 
on the french riviera 25 years ago essamelli said 
