<TEXT>
overworked underpaid compared with their peers in 
private practice and facing increasing threats from drug 
traffickers and disgruntled defendants federal judges are facing a 
crisis in the judiciary 
the situation is so bad that veteran jurists are resigning and 
the brightest lawyers are refusing to take their places saying the 
exalted status of a federal judge cant make up for what they 
consider to be a life under siege 
one of the most respected judges in the frantic southern 
district of florida resigned last week citing pressures and 
finances 
us district judge thomas e scott of miami decided to retire 
from the bench at the age of 42 after five years as a circuit judge 
and five more on the federal level 
the departure of a man widely thought of as having one of the 
top legal minds in florida was taken as an ominous sign in miamis 
legal community 
in losing tom scott were losing the equivalent of two 
judges said chief district judge james lawrence king if 
congress doesnt act soon it will leave the judiciary of south 
florida tattered and torn 
judicial workloads have more than doubled since 1969 with so 
many drug cases clogging the courts that civil litigants must wait 
years for a trial date 
