<TEXT>
families of victims in the crash of 
pan am flight 103 say they hope a public inquiry opening monday 
the first in the case will help determine how the bombing might 
have been prevented 
the inquiry is expected to look at airport security lapses but 
it wont seek to assess criminal responsibility for the crash 
families of some of the 270 victims want the investigation to 
cover security not just at londons heathrow airport but also at 
frankfurt west germany where the flight originated 
the boeing 747 was bound for new york when it blew apart over 
the small scottish town of lockerbie on dec 21 1988 eleven of 
the victims were people on the ground 
investigators say there is not enough evidence to prosecute 
anyone for the attack but they have pursued clues pointing to 
radical palestinians 
the public inquiry run by a scottish judge will be held in 
dumfries 12 miles from lockerbie the proceedings expected to 
last three months are being held in a hall converted into a 
courtroom 
the inquiry will take evidence on the planes airworthiness air 
traffic control the emergency response the deaths the 
destruction of the aircraft and security arrangements the 
scottish office said 
in a key ruling at a preliminary hearing sept 20 the judge 
rejected efforts by the british government and pan am to restrict 
evidence to britain the judge sheriff principal john s mowat 
ruled that evidence from pan am baggage handlers at frankfurt 
airport would be admissible if it he thought it relevant 
after the preliminary hearing jim swire who heads a relatives 
group called uk familiesflight 103 said he was much more 
optimistic about getting a fair hearing on how the bombing could 
have been prevented 
we have not wavered from our determination to see british 
security examined in at least the same detail as us security has 
been and we cant imagine why theyve waited 21 months even to 
start said swire his 24yearold daughter flora was killed in 
the bombing 
a us presidential commission which spent nine months 
investigating the crash reported in may that the destruction of 
flight 103 may well have been preventable 
the commission cited lapses in security including failure to 
physically search luggage transferred from other airlines it said 
no effort was made to ensure that all bags were accompanied by 
passengers 
its report called for notification of passengers when there is a 
credible bomb threat and said the united states should consider 
military strikes or covert operations against air terrorists 
swire said the families have much greater confidence in the 
scottish judiciary which is separate from the english judiciary 
we feel sure it will treat us fairly and we intend to give it 
an opportunity to do so swire said in an interview friday 
the british government has rejected the families request for an 
independent investigation saying all necessary ground would be 
covered by the continuing police investigation and the public 
hearing 
