<TEXT>
while big banks and governments fret over their 
13 trillion in lending to the third world one nonprofit group 
loaned 237 million dollars to latin americans last year and got 
virtually all of it back with interest 
seamstresses fruit vendors carpenters and thousands of other 
working poor who power half of all economic activity in latin 
america are beneficiaries of an innovative loan program developed 
by accion international 
working through affiliates in 12 latin american nations the 
massachusettsbased group provides small business loans to 
those so poor they either cannot qualify for bank loans or must 
resort to loan sharks 
we are a nonprofit organization dedicated to reducing poverty 
through the creation of jobs and increasing income said gabriela 
romanow communications director at accion international in a 
telephone interview 
accion international was founded in 1961 as a privaesector 
initiative to stimulate community development in latin america a 
network of local accion affiliates in latin capitals screen 
borrowers and approve loans at market interest rates 
more than 40 nonprofit us groups large banks and private 
donors finance the loan program as does the us agency for 
international development 
we have quite a few corporate donors and we also get money 
from foundations and individuals as well said romanow 
accions affiliates had 45000 borrowers last year who took out 
loans averaging 227 romanow said the default rate was less than 2 
percent 
the reason borrowers put up sewing machines and work tools as 
collateral individuals often apply for loans at community meetings 
or in small groups so if you dont pay back everyone knows 
romanow said 
the success stories are many like that of furniture maker ramon 
uceta who used his loans to escape poverty in santo domingo the 
dominican republic 
uceta borrowed 20 from a friend to make lamps out of wicker 
and he made three and sold them for 8 each romanow said 
he heard about accions affiliate and went in to ask for a 
loan for his wicker business about three years later after 14 
loans this man who had a tiny shack in a really poor neighborhood 
was able to expand to 14 fulltime employees 
she added he obviously has been able to move from his little 
wooden shack where he had no running water or electricity 
the loans also worked for petrona lopez of la paz bolivia who 
would occasionally beg in the city streets but has now been able to 
open her stand selling the national staple potatoes 
she and four others took out loans totaling 646 
she now has her own stall in the market instead of selling for 
other women said romanow she has been able to buy herself new 
clothing and is able to periodically to eat chicken a luxury she 
wasnt able to previously afford 
other borrowers include tailors seamstresses cobblers broom 
makers carpenters mechanics every kind of smallscale business 
that people actually do because they cant find jobs in the 
mainstream economy so they start 
she noted that studies show such workers comprise 30 percent to 
70 percent of the labor force in developing countries 
